		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St Thomas</placeName> <date>June 22<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> 1843</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isc. Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(12)">I am disappointed in not being able to re&#8222;<lb/> &#8222;mit you the amount of the subscribtion list for the Occident.<lb/> by this opportunity&#44; the fault is not mine&#44; I told the Subscri&#8222;<lb/> &#8222;bers that they might pay on receipt of the 2nd Number&#44; antici&#8222;<lb/> &#8222;parting that no retard would be experienced in the receipt of them<lb/> but to my astonishment <persName>Mr Wolff</persName> has received his <date>May</date> Number&#44;<lb/> and I have received none&#44; the Subscribers are blaming me&#44; but<lb/> I cannot help it&#44; Try &#38; send them regularly by way of <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> as there are numerous opportunities from that City for this<lb/> place&#44; I have collected from 5 Subscribers only&#44; but on receipt<lb/> of the <date>May</date> Number&#44; I will collect from the rest&#44; &#38; remit you<lb/> forthwith.   Permit me to make a few observations<lb/> which may tend to make the Occident more generally appre&#8222;<lb/> &#8222;ciated here.  Every one reads the Archives Israelites &#38; the Voice<lb/> of Jacob&#44; consequently they find the Occident not as interesting<lb/> as you could make it by extracts from the German Periodicals&#44;<lb/> this I have promise will take place.</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName>Mr Carillon</persName> is again in the Office of Minister<lb/> here&#44; and has adopted numerous innovations and alterations in<lb/> our religious forms &#38; observances.  I am decidedly averse to<lb/> such steps&#44; however much a reform might be required.  I deem<lb/> it precipitate in a Congregation like this&#44; or in any one Congre&#8222;</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>&#8222;gation to change any established order. and therefore I have<lb/> withheld all participation in their actions.&#8212;Let us await the<lb/> result of a general conclave of Enlightened &#38; religious men. &#38;<lb/> then adopt what they may determine upon.  Perhaps I may<lb/> be wrong&#44; if so please set me right.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I would send you some subject on this place<lb/> but I fear the truth would be disagreeable to your reader here<lb/> and  I prefer silence rather than injure you in any way.&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I hope soon to hear from you&#44; and pray<lb/> that the Almighty may enable you to persevere &#38; succeed in<lb/> all your undertakings&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">I am    Dear sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">M B Simmons</persName></p>
				<p>PS.  Do not laugh at me&#44; when I relate my last night&#39;s dream.&#8212;<lb/> I thought what I had long wished for had taken place&#44; that is a per&#8222;<lb/> &#8222;sonal acquaintance with your good self.  I fancied your arrival<lb/> &#38; visit to my house&#44; that you were at my table &#38; read the <add>Hebrew</add> <add>&#8220;Hamotzi&#8221; JE transcription</add> after<lb/> the meal a number of friends visited me&#44; &#38; found your conversa&#8222;<lb/> &#8222;tion so agreeable &#38; instructive&#44; that of one accord they declared you<lb/> could not be other than the <persName>Revd I. L</persName> of <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#44; while enjoying<lb/> their discovery.  I was awakened by a <hi rend="underline">shock of Earthquake</hi> in reality.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Adieu&#8212;Yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">MBS</persName></p>
				<p rend="The following is written in pencil&#44; bottom left corner.">Number &#8220;20&#45;452&#8221;</p>
		</body>
